{"batch":"design_coherence","batch_index":8,"assessments":{"design_coherence":63.0},"dimension_notes":{"design_coherence":{"evidence":["The same play-by-play normalization and possession-group setup is reimplemented in multiple scripts instead of being owned by one pipeline: `clock_to_seconds` plus `game_seconds_elapsed`/`possession_group` appear in [build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py], [categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py], [step2_build_possessions.py], and [calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py] at lines 10-19/69-87, 10-19/72-88, 22-31/38-56, and 17-26/49-67 respectively.","`build_def_foul_context` in [categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py] lines 66-171 mixes HTTP fetch, raw event cleanup, possession summarization, score-side inference, defensive-foul filtering, context-window calculation, and final CSV-row shaping in one body, so one rules change forces edits across several concerns.","The season aggregators own both dataset discovery/retry policy and domain math. [calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py] spreads season probing (`season_exists`, `game_exists`, `find_max_existing_game_number`), per-game parsing (`build_foul_vector`, `game_wmi_components`), concurrency, and final reporting across one script; [calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py] repeats a parallel version of the same possession-table logic.","Notebook checkpoint files preserve superseded structural variants alongside the active scripts. The checkpoint copies of [build_possession_model_table_okc_mil-checkpoint.py] lines 134-167 and [categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil-checkpoint.py] lines 148-169 still implement defensive-team-window logic, while the active files now implement global-window logic; the project log at [nba-whistle-project-log.md] lines 36-57 records multiple reversions between those designs."],"impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","confidence":"high"}},"issues":[{"dimension":"design_coherence","identifier":"duplicated_possession_pipeline","summary":"Core possession-building logic is copied across scripts instead of owned by one module.","related_files":["build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py","step2_build_possessions.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py"],"evidence":["[build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py] lines 63-150 fetch the feed, normalize clock/time columns, derive possession groups, count defensive fouls, and compute `L_t`/`N_t`.","[categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py] lines 66-167 repeats the same feed fetch, clock parsing, possession grouping, foul filtering, and then derives a slightly different output table.","[step2_build_possessions.py] lines 38-128 repeats the same time normalization and possession grouping yet again for another intermediate table.","[calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py] lines 42-100 embeds another copy of the same possession-table construction for season runs."],"suggestion":"Extract one shared play-by-play processing module that owns feed loading, clock normalization, team/opponent mapping, possession grouping, and defensive-foul tagging. Then have the single-game table builder, foul-context exporter, and season calculators call that module and only add their output-specific columns.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"duplicated_wmi_pipeline"},{"dimension":"design_coherence","identifier":"season_script_mixes_orchestration_and_domain_logic","summary":"The historical season runner combines season discovery, retry/network policy, parsing, and aggregation in one design.","related_files":["calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py"],"evidence":["[calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py] lines 26-85 define CDN probing and retry behavior, lines 88-153 define foul-vector and WMI math, lines 177-252 aggregate a season, and lines 255-276 handle season discovery, pacing, and CSV reporting in the same script.","[calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py] lines 29-39 define request retry policy, lines 42-100 rebuild per-game possession math, and lines 108-195 handle thread-pool orchestration, retry of failed games, aggregation, and reporting.","Because discovery/orchestration and business rules live together, changing how a season is enumerated or retried risks touching the same files that define the WMI formula."],"suggestion":"Split the season runners into three layers: a source/enumeration layer for game IDs, a reusable per-game WMI calculator, and a thin CLI/reporting script that wires them together. That keeps network policy and season enumeration from being entangled with the metric definition.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"module","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"duplicated_wmi_pipeline"},{"dimension":"design_coherence","identifier":"stale_checkpoint_variants_keep_old_design_alive","summary":"Checkpoint files keep obsolete structural variants beside the active workflow, obscuring the current design.","related_files":[".ipynb_checkpoints/build_possession_model_table_okc_mil-checkpoint.py",".ipynb_checkpoints/categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil-checkpoint.py","nba-whistle-project-log.md"],"evidence":["[.ipynb_checkpoints/build_possession_model_table_okc_mil-checkpoint.py] lines 134-167 compute prior/next windows only from the defensive team's future offensive possessions, not the current global-window rule used in the active script.","[.ipynb_checkpoints/categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil-checkpoint.py] lines 148-169 likewise preserve the earlier defensive-team-possession design.","[nba-whistle-project-log.md] lines 36-57 shows repeated reversions between global-window and defensive-team-window definitions, so leaving both code paths in tracked files makes it unclear which structure is canonical."],"suggestion":"Remove tracked `.ipynb_checkpoints` Python copies from the production tree or exclude them from the reviewed code path, and keep old formula experiments in notebooks or an explicit `experiments/` directory with dated names. That gives the project one obvious source of truth for the current design.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"module","fix_scope":"single_edit","root_cause_cluster":"superseded_design_variants"}],"retrospective":{"root_causes":["The project evolved by cloning and editing standalone scripts instead of extracting a reusable data-processing core.","Experimental formula changes were preserved as parallel file variants rather than being isolated behind one canonical implementation and one experiments area."],"likely_symptoms":["duplicated_possession_pipeline","season_script_mixes_orchestration_and_domain_logic","stale_checkpoint_variants_keep_old_design_alive"],"possible_false_positives":["The mechanical 'orphaned' signal on the top-level scripts appears mis-scoped for this repository, because [nba-whistle-project-log.md] lines 39, 45, 72, 81, and 91 show these files are run directly as manual analysis entry points rather than imported modules."]}}
